               <lb n="4"/>filiae <expan><abbr>dulciss</abbr><ex>imae</ex></expan>.
                  <lb n="5"/>
               <expan><abbr>Vix</abbr><ex>it</ex></expan> annis <num value="2">II</num>,
                  <lb n="6"/>
               <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>ensibus</ex></expan>
               <num value="8">VIII</num>, <expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>iebus</ex></expan>
               <num value="15">XV</num>.
               </ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. To Peducaea Graptusa, dearest daughter. She lived for
               two years, eight months, (and) fifteen days.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This inscription is a copy of an epitaph published by A. W. van Buren, <hi rend="italic">Classical Studies in honor of John C. Rolfe</hi> (Philadelphia 1931) 317, who reports that the original, along with another epitaph (EDR033467), was 'obtained' by an antiquarian dealer, Armando Pacifici (when is unknown) 'near the Velodromo on the Via Appia Nova' and was last known to have been preserved in his premises at via Foro Romano in 1931. The stamped design in the lower left corner was probably added during the copying process.</p>
         </div>
